1497","1471–1497":"1471–1497","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","about 1518":"about 1518","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1498":"1498","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1497":"1497","1486":"1486","about 1520":"about 1520","after 1497":"after 1497","1549":"1549","Pimhill, Shropshire, England":"Pimhill, Shropshire, England","Longdon, Staffordshire, England":"Longdon, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for someone who habitually wore a distinctive pair of boots or gaiters, from Old French <i>hosed</i>, <i>hoset</i>, <i>housé</i>, Middle English <i>hosey</i>, <i>hus(s)y</i>,‘booted, gaitered’ (from Latin <i>hosatus</i>).","English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>hus(e)wyf</i> ‘mistress of a family; wife of a householder’ (a compound of Old English <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>wīf</i> ‘woman’). Though originally a woman's name, it is often found as a male surname, presumably in a derogatory sense. The vocabulary word became <i>hussie</i>, with the meaning ‘disreputable woman’, in the 16th century; the surname, however, is not associated with this meaning.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":51,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":60,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Hussey was born in 1498, in Pimhill, Shropshire, England, her father, Richard Hussey, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. Hussey, was 28. She married Humphrey Ruggeley about 1518, in Longdon, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 